List comprehensions can contain more then one for and if clauses:

[
(x, y) 
for x in range(4) 
for y in range (x + 2) 
if x != 0 
if y != x
]

Compare two dictionaries:

>>> a = {'x' : 0, 'y': 1, 'z' : 3}
>>> b = {'x' : 0, 'y': 1, 'z' : 2, 'q' : 4}
>>> a.items() & b.items()
{('y', 1), ('x', 0)}
>>> a.items() ^ b.items()
{('z', 3), ('q', 4), ('z', 2)}
>>> a.items() - b.items()
{('z', 3)}

